    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:48acd48e-3969-4926-a8cb-d1ad0d26d17e",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 9-year-old boy who appears tired, pale, and mildly uncomfortable, sitting curled slightly forward on the exam table and intermittently holding his abdomen. Over the past 2 days he has developed frequent loose watery stools, crampy diffuse abdominal pain, reduced appetite, and several episodes of non-bloody vomiting. His lips are a little dry and he asks for water often, but he remains alert, interactive, and appropriately responsive for his age. He has had a low-grade fever at home and seems less energetic than usual, preferring to lie on the couch rather than play.\n\nHe lives with his parents and a younger sister and is in primary school. Normally, {patientName} is active and social, enjoys football at recess, rides his bicycle in the neighborhood, and spends time building with toy blocks and playing age-appropriate video games. His diet is somewhat selective but typical for a school-aged child, with a preference for pasta, chicken, yogurt, bananas, and fruit juice. His parents report he recently attended a weekend birthday party where several children later developed \"stomach flu\" symptoms.\n\nAt baseline, {patientName} is healthy, growing well, and has no developmental concerns. He has close family support, and his mother has been encouraging oral fluids at home using small frequent sips. He has missed 2 days of school because of diarrhea and fatigue. The family is worried mainly about dehydration because he has been urinating less often than usual.\n\nOn general observation, he has mild signs of dehydration but no toxic appearance. His abdomen is soft with diffuse mild tenderness and active bowel sounds, without guarding or rebound. There is no rash, no jaundice, and no respiratory distress. The overall presentation is consistent with an acute infectious gastroenteritis causing fluid losses and temporary systemic malaise."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:6b31e0a0-23c6-4f20-954c-daa6e84ae4e1",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has no significant chronic medical conditions and no prior history of inflammatory bowel disease, chronic diarrhea, or food intolerance. His immunizations are up to date for age. He has never been hospitalized, and there is no history of abdominal surgery. His parents report a similar but milder self-limited stomach illness about 2 years ago that resolved at home without complications.\n\nOver the last 48 hours, {patientName} has had 6-8 loose stools per day and 3 episodes of non-bilious, non-bloody emesis. He has had decreased appetite and lower fluid intake, with reduced urine output since the previous evening. No recent antibiotic exposure is reported, making Clostridioides difficile less likely. There has been no recent foreign travel, but he did attend a social event with likely sick contacts.\n\nHe is generally active, sleeps well, and does not use any substances. There is no household smoking inside the home, though his father occasionally smokes outdoors. His baseline medications are limited to occasional seasonal allergy treatment and routine over-the-counter pediatric supplements. There is no known immunodeficiency, renal disease, or endocrine disorder."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
